<subSubSection id="C3616545FFF9BF13FF47479EFF44FD30" pageId="27" pageNumber="284" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC436CEFFF9BF13FF47479EFCDDFDF8" blockId="27.[151,1436,151,680]" pageId="27" pageNumber="284">
<emphasis id="B90FEADCFFF9BF13FF47479EFED0FE6D" bold="true" box="[199,335,476,501]" pageId="27" pageNumber="284">Comments.</emphasis>
This cryptic species was revealed by its barcode. The specimen from Crete (Asprouliani) barcoded by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEA4B3FFFF9BF13FEB647BDFDA5FD80" box="[310,570,511,536]" pageId="27" pageNumber="284" refString="Schmidt, S., Schmid-Egger, C., Moriniere, J., Haszprunar, G. &amp; Hebert, P. D. N. (2015) DNA barcoding largely supports 250 years of classical taxonomy: identifications for Central European bees (Hymenoptera, Apoidea partim). Molecular Ecology Resources, 15 (4), 985 - 1000. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / 1755 - 0998.12363" type="journal article">
Schmidt 
<emphasis id="B90FEADCFFF9BF13FE214443FE7EFD80" box="[417,481,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="284">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number id="3DB324E9FFF9BF13FE7747BDFDADFD80" box="[503,562,511,536]" pageId="27" pageNumber="284" value="2015.0">2015</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
has a barcode positioned at the base of the cluster (
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D4DFFF9BF13FB4B4442FAC4FD80" authority="Robertson, 1918" authorityName="Robertson" authorityYear="1918" box="[1227,1371,511,536]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Seladonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="284" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gemmella">
<emphasis id="B90FEADCFFF9BF13FB4B4442FAC4FD80" box="[1227,1371,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="284">S. gemmella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D4DFFF9BF13FA074442FECAFDA5" authority="Robertson, 1918" authorityName="Robertson" authorityYear="1918" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Seladonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="284" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="submediterranea">
<emphasis id="B90FEADCFFF9BF13FA074442FECAFDA5" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="284">S. submediterranea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D4DFFF9BF13FE014467FD8EFDA4" authority="Robertson, 1918" authorityName="Robertson" authorityYear="1918" box="[385,529,549,572]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Seladonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="284" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orientana">
<emphasis id="B90FEADCFFF9BF13FE014467FD8EFDA4" box="[385,529,549,572]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="284">S. orientana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Unfortunately, the genitalia of the few collected specimens could not be photographed with a scanning electron microscope for study.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC436CEFFF9BF13FF47442EFF44FD30" blockId="27.[151,1436,151,680]" pageId="27" pageNumber="284">
<emphasis id="B90FEADCFFF9BF13FF47442EFEDFFD1D" bold="true" box="[199,320,620,645]" pageId="27" pageNumber="284">Variations</emphasis>
. Specimens from Karpathos have antennae dark below while they are brown in the specimens from Crete.
</paragraph>
